7_1368126251839_352&quot;&gt;&lt;div id=&quot;yiv1276886991yui_3_7_2_27_1368126251839_351&quot; class=&quot;yiv1276886991yui_3_7_2_27_1368126251839_85&quot; style=&quot;color:#000;background-color:#fff;font-family:arial, helvetica, sans-serif;font-size:10pt;&quot;&gt;Dear Rajarshi and others,&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;Have a great solar eclipse! This is a really nice occasion for extra \nmeditation or extra homam or extra contemplation or extra \nphilosophization.&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;*&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; *&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; *&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;&gt; &lt;span id=&quot;yiv1276886991yui_3_7_2_27_1368126251839_619&quot;&gt;Now lets get into more subtle, precise analysis :)&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/span&gt;I asked for trouble, didn&#39;t I? :-)&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;*&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; *&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; *&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;&gt; this apparent conflict between what Rishi Parashara&lt;br&gt;&gt; states and what this Purana states&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;There may be some confusion regarding &quot;poornavatara&quot;.&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;As Parasara used it, the term &quot;poornavatara&quot; does NOT mean &quot;the most complete or perfect avatara&quot;. It means a completely divine avatara with no jivamsa. There can be more than one poornavataras. They are not necessarily &quot;equal&quot;.&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;To give a simplisitc analogy, some jewllery may be gold mixed with some amount of\n copper. If one jewllery is 100% pure gold, it\n does not mean\n it contains all the gold in the\n world. It only means it has nothing other than gold. Similarly, the four poornavataras mentioned by Parasara are 100% divine and do not contain jivamsa. It does not mean they contain &quot;all the divinity&quot; in cosmos.&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;*&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; *&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; *&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;In fact, the very notion that any one form can be &quot;the most complete or perfect avatara&quot; or &quot;one that personifies entire divinity of Supreme Being&quot; or &quot;one equal to Supreme Being&quot; is unacceptable and inconsistent with SB 1.3.30-31, which says that ANY form of Supreme Being is like a cloud in the sky, while Supreme Being is like the sky containing all possible clouds.&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;Supreme Being is endowed with infinite qualities. Any form contains a finite number of those qualities. So no form can be &quot;equal to&quot; Supreme Being. SB 1.3.30-31 is clear in that regard.&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;If one\n form is &quot;equal to&quot; supreme being and others are\n not, you can conclude that that form is &quot;the best&quot;. If neither form is &quot;equal to&quot; supreme being, how can you really compare the different qualities of two forms?&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;*&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; *&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; *&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;Anyway, this renders your (3) a meaningless issue. Whether that line refers to Krishna alone or not is irrelevant, for, in either case, &quot;swayam bhagavan&quot; cannot mean &quot;a personification of the entirety of supreme being&quot;. Before you wonder whether it refers to Krishna alone or not, first figure out what &quot;swayam bhagavan&quot; actually means, in a way that is not inconsistent with verses that follow! If no form is &quot;equal to&quot; supreme being and every form is a &quot;subset&quot; of supreme being (like a cloud in sky), what is the meaning of &quot;swayam bhagavan&quot;???&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;*&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\n *&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; *&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;Regarding (4), Parasara\n identified 4 avataras as 100% divine, with no jivamsa, and identified the source of divinity in each of them. He only gave objective information and did not give any subjective judgment on who is the best, which Suta apparently did.&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;I have not read BV Purana. If you can quote some verses before and after, I can comment. Any comparison between avataras WILL have to be under some subjective context. I don&#39;t know the context of Suta&#39;s statement you allude to.&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;Though any comparison is subjective, I will be surprised if someone considers the other two poornavataras of Vishnu as the &quot;best&quot; avataras. But, I will not be surprised if different people consider Rama and Krishna as the most perfect avataras. Sun and Moon are the luminaries and show soul and mind, which clearly have a primary significance compared to other aspects of consciousness! So Rama and Krishna are bound to be seen as the best by different people.\n However, what Suta\n apparently said can only be a subjective view under some context.&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;*&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; *&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; *&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;Regarding (2): Kala means a part or a phase. Moon has 16 phases (representing 16 tithis, including Amavasya and Pournima), but Sun has only one phase - he is always full and bright!&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;Just like Moon, mind has many moods, even a perfected one. A perfected mind goes through those moods with full awareness of underlying reality, whereas an imperfect mind experiences them under delusion. But it is the nature of Moon/mind to have variations. Sun/soul OTOH has no such variations.&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;Krishna may show Vishwaroopa oneday, run away from battlefield another day (e.g. Jarasandha), do amazing miracles oneday and play clever tricks another day. There is a lot more variety to his personality than Rama&#39;s. Now, does that make him better or worse than Rama? Well, that\n is\n a *subjective* matter.&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;*&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; *&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; *&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;Regarding (1): Parasara said that paramatmamsa is present in several beings such a planets, Brahma, Shiva, their consorts, etc. Grahas sustain the world appearance in consciousness by grasping it based on karmaphala. So they stand for different qualities of Vishnu that sustain the world appearance. So Vishnu&#39;s avataras are associated with grahas. But Pararsara said that avataras can descend from the paramatmamsa present in several other beings (e.g. Shiva, Parvati, Ashwins, Maruts etc). Unfortunately, we have meagre understanding what various deities stand for, what forces play a role in creating, sustaining and destroying the world appearance in consciousness. People talk too much about Vedanta (end of Veda) and there is hardly any understanding of Veda. When it comes to Puranic stories, we think in terms of\n superficial stories and not in terms of how it maps to what happens in consciousness.&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;Mohini was an avatara of Vishnu + Maheshwari. Nara &amp; Narayana were incarnations of Narayana (i.e. Brahma + Vishnu + Shiva). I don&#39;t know about Dhanvantari and will pass for today. Dattatreya again was an incarnation of Shiva + Vishnu + Brahma. Balarama is an incarnation of great serpent Adi Sesha (like Lakshmana).&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;We need to go deeper into what they all stand for esoterically and what role they play in the functioning of consciousness, to understand this more. Hopefully another day..&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;*&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; *&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; *&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;Adwaitins who are skeptical about notions taught by Parasara (paramatmamsa, jivatmamsa, different sources of paramtmamsa etc) should realize one thing. Though all is Brahman, all did not come from Brahman in one step. It all evolved in many\n steps\n and correspondingly there are some steps in the process of liberation!&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;If a character in my dream tonight overcomes its conditioning in the dream, it will simply merge back into my mind and not into Brahman yet. Of course, it cannot do even that until I actually will it. It is after all a character created and sustained in my mind!&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;Same thing applies to us!&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;Vedanta is not wrong. But it is relevant and applicable at &quot;anta&quot;, i.e. the end. Most of us may not yet be anywhere near &quot;the end&quot;.&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;*&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; *&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; *&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;BTW, I distinguished between Vishnu and \nNarayana above. If you study Narayana sooktam and Vishnu Sooktam, you \ncan understand the difference. In Vaishnava traditions, they are \nconsidered one, but, strictly speaking, that is inaccurate. Of course, \nyou can reach Narayana through Vishnu. But then, you can reach Narayana \nthrough Rudra or Bhairava as well!&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;*&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; *&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; *&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;&gt; I am afraid the world will keep getting more and more convinced that&lt;br&gt;&gt; this specific list of dasavataras represent a parable of evoluion&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;The *world*? You mean the world of Rajarshi? ;-)&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;World accepts 10 avataras where Kalki will be the 10th (and not 9th as you suggested, to fit your notion of evolution). Even those who are uncomfortable with Buddha replace him with someone else rather than make it 9 avataras. World neither thinks much about this nor draws hasty conclusions. World really does not care about this..&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;Best regards,&lt;br&gt;Narasimha&lt;br&gt;--------&lt;br&gt;Astrology &amp; Spirituality Resources: http://www.VedicAstrologer.org &lt;br&gt;--------&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;&lt;div id=&quot;yiv1276886991yui_3_7_2_37_1367796055441_335&quot;&gt;&lt;blockquote\n id=&quot;yiv1276886991yui_3_7_2_3